<fig id="img1-2041669517707768" orientation="portrait" position="anchor"><graphic xlink:href="10.1177_2041669517707768-img1"/></fig>
</p><p><bold>Behrang Keshavarz</bold> is a scientist at the Toronto Rehabilitation Institute and an adjunct professor at the Department of Psychology at Ryerson University, Toronto. He received his PhD in 2012 in Psychology from the Johannes Gutenberg-University Mainz, Germany. His research focuses on human factors in virtual environments, motion sickness and simulator sickness, the neurocognitive and behavioral aspects of vection, and driving simulation research.</p><p>
<fig id="img2-2041669517707768" orientation="portrait" position="anchor"><graphic xlink:href="10.1177_2041669517707768-img2"/></fig>
</p><p><bold>Martina Speck</bold> is a graduate clinical psychology student at the Department for Psychology at the Johannes Gutenberg-University Mainz, Germany. Her research interests include visual perception, fear, and emotion.</p><p>
<fig id="img3-2041669517707768" orientation="portrait" position="anchor"><graphic xlink:href="10.1177_2041669517707768-img3"/></fig>
</p><p><bold>Bruce Haycock</bold> is a scientist at the Toronto Rehabilitation Institute and an assistant professor in the University of Toronto Institute for Aerospace Studies. His research focus is primarily human in the loop vehicle simulation, including simulator technologies, vehicle dynamics, and human control of vehicles.</p><p>
<fig id="img4-2041669517707768" orientation="portrait" position="anchor"><graphic xlink:href="10.1177_2041669517707768-img4"/></fig>
</p><p><bold>Stefan Berti</bold> is an associate professor at the Department for Psychology at the Johannes Gutenberg-University Mainz, Germany. He studied Psychology and Sport Sciences at the Universities of Frankfurt, Giessen and Leipzig and received his PhD in Psychology in 2001 (University of Leipzig, Germany); since 2003 he works at the Johannes Gutenberg-University Mainz. His current research interests are the neurocognitive underpinnings of working memory, attention, and vection.</p></bio></back></article>